'''Abu Saʿīd Abdul-Hay ibn <u>Dh</u>aḥḥāk ibn Maḥmūd Gardēzī''', '''Gardīzī''' or '''Gurdēzī''' (died c. 1061 CE) ({{lang-fa|ابوسعید عبدالحی بن ضحاک بن محمود گردیزی}}) was a [[Persian people|Persian]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bosworth|first1=C. Edmund|title=GARDĪZĪ, ABŪ SAʿĪD ʿABD-al-ḤAYY|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/gardizi|publisher=ENCYCLOPÆDIA IRANICA|accessdate=2 December 2016|quote=GARDĪZĪ, ABŪ SAʿĪD ʿABD-al-ḤAYY b. Żaḥḥāk b. Maḥmūd, Persian historian of the early 5th/11th century.}}</ref> [[Muslim]] [[geographer]] and [[historian]] of the early 11th century from [[Gardez|Gardēz]] in modern [[Afghanistan]].<ref>''Gardizi'', W. Barthold, ''The Encyclopaedia of Islam'', Vol.II, ed. B. Lewis, C. Pellat and J. Schacht, (Brill, 1991), p. 978.</ref> He wrote the book ''Zayn al-A<u>kh</u>bār'' while at the court of Abdul-Rashid, sultan of the [[Ghaznavids|Ghaznavid Empire]].<ref>''Historiography in the Sadduzai Era:Language and Narration'', Senzil Nawid, ''Literacy in the Persianate World: Writing and the Social Order'', ed. [[Brian J. Spooner|Brian Spooner]] and William Hanaway, (University of Pennsylvania Press, 2012), 235.</ref> Gardēzī's work, written in Persian, is an [[Islam]]ic history of [[Central Asia]] and Eastern [[Greater Iran|Persia]] and [[Hungary]].
== Work == In his ''Zayn al-akbar'', Gardīzī took a dispassionate view of history which was fairly remarkable for its time.<ref name="Iranica">[http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/gardizi "''GARDĪZĪ, ABŪ SAʿĪD ʿABD-al-ḤAYY'' GARDĪZĪ,ABŪ SAʿĪD ʿABD-al-ḤAYY b. Żaḥḥāk b. Maḥmūd in Encyclopedia Iranica by C. EDMUND BOSWORTH]</ref> It consisted of a history of the pre-Islamic kings of Persia, Muhammad and the Caliphs until the year 1032. Included is a history of the Arab invasion of Khurasan, which it is believed Gardizi was using al-Sallami as a source. His history concerning the Turks was written using [[Ibn Khordadbeh]], al-Djayhani and Ibn al-Mukaffa as sources.<ref name="ReferenceA">''Gardizi'', W. Barthold, ''The Encyclopaedia of Islam'', Vol.II, p. 978.</ref> He may have been a student of [[Abū Rayḥān al-Bīrūnī|al-Biruni]], since the ''Zayn al-akbar'' contains information concerning Indian festivals.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> His style of Persian is simple but mature and provides one of the classical examples of Persian prose-writing. A critical edition was published by ʿAbd al-Ḥayy Ḥabībī, Tehran, 1347 Š./1968 under the title of "''Tarikh-e Gardizi''".
