{{Chinese name|[[Li (surname 郦)|Li]]}}

'''Li Daoyuan''' ({{zh|t=酈道元|s=郦道元|p=Lì Dàoyuán}}; 466 or 472 in [[Zhuo County]], [[Hebei]] – 527) was a Chinese geographer, writer, and politician during the [[Northern Wei Dynasty]]. He is known as the author of the ''[[Commentary on the Water Classic]]'' (''Shuijingzhu''), a monumental work on China's geography in ancient times.<ref name="Jing2002">{{cite book|last=Jing|first=Anning|title=The Water God's Temple of the Guangsheng Monastery: Cosmic Function of Art, Ritual and Theater|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XisCyZQIFDkC&pg=PA108|year=2002|publisher=BRILL|isbn=90-04-11925-6|page=108}}</ref>

Li Daoyuan used his position as an official with business in different places to carry field investigations. He is known to have visited the area belonging to the present-day [[Henan]], [[Shandong]], [[Shanxi]], and [[Jiangsu]] provinces.<ref name="chinaculture1">China Culture.org. "[http://www.chinaculture.org/gb/en_madeinchina/2005-09/02/content_72434.htm Li Daoyuan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203150120/http://www.chinaculture.org/gb/en_madeinchina/2005-09/02/content_72434.htm |date=2008-12-03 }}".</ref><ref name="chinaculture2">China Culture.org. "[http://www.chinaculture.org/gb/en_aboutchina/2003-09/24/content_22574.htm Commentary on the Waterways Classic] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820205230/http://www.chinaculture.org/gb/en_aboutchina/2003-09/24/content_22574.htm |date=2008-08-20 }}".</ref>

Another source for his knowledge was the study of ancient geographical books he had access to, like the ''[[Shan Hai Jing|Classic of Mountains and Seas]]'' (''Shanhaijing'') completed by the time of the early [[Western Han Dynasty]]) and the ''[[Water Classic]]'' (''Shuijing''), written by Sang Qin during the [[Three Kingdoms Period]] and later commentated on by Jin dynasty writer [[Guo Pu]]. Li vastly expanded the ''Water Classic'', doing his own research and fieldwork. The original ''[[Water Classic]]'' has not survived but covered 127 rivers and streams and contained about 10,000 characters;<ref name="chinaculture1"/> Li Daoyuan's ''Commentary on the Waterways Classic'' ([[Shui Jing Zhu]], discusses 1252 watercourses and contains about 300,000 characters in total.<ref name=chinaculture2/> The book maps and describes the rivers and streams along with the history, geography and culture of the surrounding region.

